{"title_page": "Willa Brown", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{short description|American aviator, educator, activist}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name        = Willa Brown\n|image       = \"Willa Beatrice Brown, a 31-year-old Negro American, serves her country by training pilots for the U.S. Army Air Forces. - NARA - 535717.jpg\n|alt         =\n|caption     = Brown as a lieutenant in the [[United States Civil Air Patrol]]\n|birth_date  = {{birth date|mf=yes|1906|01|22}}\n|birth_place = [[Glasgow, Kentucky]], US\n|death_date  = {{death date and age|mf=yes|1992|07|18|1906|01|22}}\n|death_place = [[Chicago, Illinois]], US\n|other_names = Willa Brown Chappell\n|known_for   = [[Civil rights]] leader<br/>First female African American pilot licensed in the United States<br/>First African American officer in the United States Civil Air Patrol<br/>First African American woman to run for [[United States Congress]]\n|occupation  = [[Pilot (aeronautics)|Pilot]], [[lobbyist]], [[activist]], [[teacher]]\n|spouse   = {{Marriage|Wilbur Hardaway|November 24, 1929|1931|div}}<br>{{Marriage|[[Cornelius Coffey]]|7 February 1947|end=div}}<br>{{Marriage|Rev. J. H. Chappell|1955|end=death}}\n}}\n'''Willa Beatrice Brown''' (January 22, 1906&nbsp;\u2013 July 18, 1992) was an American [[Pilot (aeronautics)|aviator]], [[lobbyist]], [[teacher]], and [[Civil Rights Movement|civil rights]] activist.<ref name=\"anb\">{{cite web |last1=Gubert |first1=Betty Kaplan |title=Brown, Willa (1906-1992), pilot and aviation educator |url=http://www.anb.org/articles/20/20-01864.html |website=American National Biography |publisher=Oxford University Press |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en| url-access=subscription}}</ref> She was the first [[African American]] woman to earn a pilot's license in the United States,<ref name=\"blackpast\">{{Cite web|title = Brown, Willa B. (1906\u20131992) |url = http://www.blackpast.org/aah/brown-willa-b-1906-1992|website = The Black Past|author=Davis, Edmond|access-date = 2016-02-09}}</ref> the first African American woman to run for the [[United States Congress]], first African American officer in the [[Civil Air Patrol]], and first woman in the U.S. to have both a pilot's license and an aircraft mechanic's license.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"DOM\"/> \n\nShe was a lifelong advocate for gender and racial equality in the field of aviation as well as in the military. She not only lobbied the U.S. government to integrate the [[United States Army Air Corps]] and include African Americans in the Civilian Pilot Training Program (CPTP), she and [[Cornelius Coffey]] co-founded the [[Coffey School of Aeronautics]], distinguishing it as the first private flight training academy owned and operated by African Americans in the United States. She trained hundreds of pilots, several of whom went on to become [[Tuskegee Airmen]]; the creation of the Tuskegee Airmen has been credited to Brown's training efforts.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Our History {{!}} 99s in Aviation History {{!}} Women in Aviation |first=Kelli|last=Grant|url = http://www.ninety-nines.org/women-in-aviation-article.htm|website = The Ninety-Nines, Inc.|access-date =February 9, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"kchr.ky.gov 2020\">{{cite web | title=Willa Brown Chappell | website=kchr.ky.gov | date=2020-03-31 | url=https://kchr.ky.gov/ggbk/Pages/gbk33.aspx | access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nBrown remained politically and socially active in [[Chicago]] long after the Coffey School closed in 1945. She ran in Congressional primary elections in 1946 and 1950 and taught in the Chicago Public School System until 1971, when she retired at age 65. Following her retirement, she served on the Federal Aviation Administration's Women's Advisory Committee until 1974.\n\n== Early life ==\nWilla Beatrice Brown was born to Reverend and Mrs. Erice B. Brown on January 22, 1906, in [[Glasgow, Kentucky]].<ref name=\"blackpast\"/> She graduated from Wiley High School in [[Terre Haute, Indiana]], and attended [[Indiana State University|Indiana State Teachers College]] where she graduated in 1927 with a bachelor's degree. Ten years later she earned an [[M.B.A.]] from [[Northwestern University]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|title=Black Women in America: An Historical Encyclopedia|year=1994|publisher=Indiana University Press | location= Bloomington |isbn=0-253-32774-1 | pages=184\u2013185 | chapter=Brown, Willa Beatrice (1906\u20131992)|first=Elizabeth Hadley|last=Freydberg}}</ref><ref name=\"Davis 2012\">{{cite web | last=Davis | first=Edmond | title=Willa B. Brown (1906-1992) | website=BlackPast | date=2012-07-25 | url=https://www.blackpast.org/african-american-history/brown-willa-b-1906-1992/ | access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nBrown taught in [[Gary, Indiana]] at [[Emerson High School (Indiana)|Emerson High School]]'s [[Theodore Roosevelt College and Career Academy#History|Roosevelt Annex]] from 1927 to 1932.<ref name=\"Davis 2012\"/><ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\"/> She then moved to Chicago, where she worked in a variety of jobs, including secretarial work, social work, and teaching.<ref name=\"notable-black-american-women\">{{cite book |last1=Smith |first1=Jessie Carney |title=Notable Black American women |publisher=Gale Research |isbn=978-0810391772 |pages=69\u201371}}</ref> In 1934, she met [[John Robinson (aviator)|John C. Robinson]], who introduced her to the Challenger Air Pilots Association, a group of African American pilots.<ref name=\"anb\"/>\n\n== Aviation career ==\n[[File:Young Willa Brown.jpg|thumb|A young Willa Brown on an airfield]]\n[[File:Lola Albright and Willa Brown.jpg|thumb|Lola Albright (left) and Willa Brown (right) at Harlem Airport, Chicago Illinois, USA]]\nIn 1934, Brown began studying at Chicago's racially segregated Harlem Field with certified flight instructor [[Cornelius Coffey]], an expert in the field of aviation mechanics. She was one of few women who attended [[Curtiss\u2013Wright Aeronautical University]] where she studied aircraft maintenance and earned an aircraft mechanic's license in 1935.<ref name=\"DOM\">{{cite web | title=Masterful Willa Brown (1906-1992) | website=DOM Magazine | date=2010-01-01 | url=https://dommagazine.com/article/masterful-willa-brown-1906-1992 | access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\">{{cite book |last1=Gubert |first1=Betty Kaplan |last2=Sawyer |first2=Miriam |last3=Fannin |first3=Caroline |title=Distinguished African Americans in aviation and space science |publisher=Oryx Press |isbn=978-1573562461 |pages=49\u201352|location=Westport, Conn.|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/distinguishedafr00gube}}</ref> She earned a private pilot's license in 1938<ref>{{cite news |title=Young Woman Flyer Gets Pilot License: Willa Brown, Chicago Aviatrix, Can Carry Passengers, Give Instructions or Make Cross-Country Flights |work=The Pittsburgh Courier |date=2 July 1938 |page=11}}</ref> and a commercial pilot's license in 1939, becoming the first African American woman to earn either type of license in the United States.<ref name=\"anb\" /><ref name=\"chicago-tribune\">{{cite news |title=Chicago and the Tuskegee Airmen |work=Chicago Tribune |date=January 19, 2015 |page=Sec. 1 - 14 |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/opinion/editorials/ct-tuskegee-airmen-chicago-world-war-ii-willa-brown-edit-0119-jm-20150119-story.html}}</ref>{{efn|[[Bessie Coleman]] was the first black American, male or female, to earn an international pilot's license which she obtained in France in the 1920s, whereas Brown was the first black American woman to earn a pilot's license in the U.S.<ref name=DOM/><ref name=\"kchr.ky.gov 2020\" /><ref name=\"chicago-tribune\" /><ref name=\"Dawson Bowles 2005 p. 5\">{{cite book | last=Dawson | first=V.P. | last2=Bowles | first2=M.D. | title=Realizing the Dream of Flight: Biographical Essays in Honor of the Centennial of Flight, 1903-2003 | publisher=National Aeronautics and Space Administration, NASA History Division, Office of External Relations | series=NASA SP | year=2005 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NpIpJI7nYV4C&pg=PA5 | access-date=2020-04-05 | page=5}}</ref>}}\n\nWilla Brown, Cornelius Coffey and Enoch P. Waters worked together to form the National Negro Airmen Association of America, later renamed to National Airmen's Association of America which was incorporated in 1939. Their primary mission was to attract more interest in aviation, help develop a better understanding in the field of aeronautics, and increase African American participation in both fields.<ref name=\"Lest We Forget 1939\">{{cite web | title=National Airmen Association of America: Tuskegee Airmen | website=Lest We Forget | date=1939-08-16 | url=http://lestweforget.hamptonu.edu/page.cfm?uuid=9FEC42B7-EB34-45CE-CC673CA72120E420 | access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> Brown was the national secretary and president of the organization's Chicago branch, and an activist for racial equality. She also took on public relations duties for the organization, and flew to colleges and spoke on the radio to get African Americans interested in flying.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\"/> She and Coffey started the Coffey School of Aeronautics in Chicago, located at Harlem Airport. They established the school for the purpose of training black pilots and teaching aviation mechanics.<ref name=\"cap-bio\">{{cite web |last1=Montague |first1=Carlos |title=Willa Brown: Pioneer for Female & African American Aviation |url=https://www.cap.news/willa-brown-pioneer-for-female--african-american-aviation/ |website=Willa Brown: Pioneer for Female & African American Aviation |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=en-us}}</ref> \n\n[[File:LIEUT. WILLA BROWN - AVIATRIX-MAKER OF PILOTS - NARA - 535627.tif|thumb|Office for Emergency Management publication featuring Brown]]\nShe lobbied the government as an advocate for the integration of black pilots into a then-segregated [[United States Army Air Corps|Army Air Corps]] and federal [[Civilian Pilot Training Program]] (CPTP).  She also worked to disprove a 1925 [[United States Army War College|Army War College]] study which had deemed African Americans unfit to fly.<ref name=\"chicago-tribune\" /> She lobbied the federal government to award CPTP contracts to train African American pilots. In 1940, she was appointed coordinator of the Chicago units of the CPTP, and the Coffey School was selected by the U.S. Army Air Corps as a feeder school to provide black students to its pilot training program.<ref name=\"notable-black-american-women\" /> Nearly 200 students from the school went on to join the [[Tuskeegee Airmen]].<ref name=\"tuskegee-airmen\">{{cite web |title=Willa Beatrice Brown |url=http://tuskegeeairmen.org/wp-content/uploads/Willa-Brown-Bio.pdf |website=Tuskegee Airmen Inc. |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> In 1942, she attained the rank of Lieutenant in Civil Air Patrol Squadron 613-6, becoming the first African American officer in the Civil Air Patrol.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\"/> She was later appointed war-training service coordinator for the [[Civil Aeronautics Authority]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Willa Brown |url=http://www.hill.af.mil/library/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=5858 |website=Hill Air Force Base |accessdate=30 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160328143509/http://www.hill.af.mil/library/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=5858 |archivedate=28 Mar 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Postwar career ==\nIn 1946, Brown ran in the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] primary elections for [[Illinois's 1st congressional district]], becoming the first African American woman to run in a congressional primary election. Her campaign focused on improving the opportunities for African Americans, including creating an airport owned and used by African Americans.<ref>{{cite news |title=Willa B. Brown Views Politics as New Crusade |work=Chicago Daily Tribune |date=31 Mar 1946 |page=S4}}</ref> She was defeated by William E. King.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wilson |first1=Edward |title=Busbey Victory Outstanding in Congress Races |work=Chicago Daily Tribune |date=11 Apr 1946 |page=2}}</ref> She ran for the same Congressional seat in the 1950 Republican primary election, and was defeated by [[Archibald Carey Jr.]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Harold |title=G. O. P. Starts Work to Regain Congress Posts: Leaders Hail Primary Spats as Robustness |work=Chicago Daily Tribune |date=13 Apr 1950 |page=19}}</ref>\n\nBrown returned to teaching in high schools from 1962 until her retirement in 1971. She taught business and aeronautics.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\" /> She served on the Women's Advisory Committee of the [[Federal Aviation Administration]] from 1972 to 1975. She was the first black woman to serve on that committee.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\"/>\n\n== Personal life ==\nBrown was married three times. Her first marriage was to Wilbur J. Hardaway, an African American firefighter. They met while Brown was teaching in Gary, Indiana, married in 1929, and divorced in 1931.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\"/>\n\nBrown was described as follows:\n{{quote|text=When Willa Brown, a shapely young brownskin woman, wearing white johdpurs, a form fitting white jacket and white boots, strode into our newsroom, in 1936, she made such a stunning appearance that all the typewriters suddenly went silent...Unlike most visitors, [she] wasn't at all bewildered. She had a confident bearing and there was an undercurrent of determination in her husky voice as she announced, not asked, that she wanted to see me.|author=Enoch P. Waters<ref>{{Cite news |last=Bolden |first=Tonya |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8j6pDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT54&lpg=PT54 |title=Changing the Equation: 50+ US Black Women in STEM |date=March 3, 2020 |access-date=April 14, 2020 |publisher=Abrams |language=en |isbn=978-1-68335-629-5}}</ref>}}\n\nIn 1947, she and Cornelius Coffey married, but the marriage did not last long. Her final marriage was to Reverend J. H. Chappell, pastor of the Chicago West Side Community Church, in 1955.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\"/> She was a widow by 1991.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/26618726/black-female-flyer-gave-life-to-aviation/ |title=Black female flyer gave life to aviation |date=March 23, 1991 |work=The Dispatch |access-date=April 13, 2020 |pages=4}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and recognition ==\n*In 1939, Brown was cited in the 76th [[Congressional Record]] for achievements in aviation.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\" />\n*''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine profiled Brown in its September 25, 1939 issue.<ref>{{Cite magazine|date=September 25, 1939|volume=34|issue=13|page=20|periodical=[[TIME Magazine]]|title=School for Willa}}</ref>\n*In 2002, [[Women in Aviation International]] named Brown one of the 100 most influential women in aviation and space.<ref>{{cite web |title=100 Most Influential Women in the Aviation and Aerospace Industry {{!}} Women in Aviation International |url=https://www.wai.org/pioneers/100womenscript |website=www.wai.org |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n*In 2003, a decade after her death, Willa Beatrice Brown was inducted into the [[Kentucky Aviation Hall of Fame]].<ref name=\"DOM\" /><ref name=\"Kentucky Women\">{{cite web | title=Willa Beatrice Brown | website=Kentucky Women's History Project | date=June 20, 2014| url=http://www.kywomenshistoryproject.com/willa-beatrice-brown-2/ | access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n*In 2010, Brown was awarded the Distinguished Alumni Award by the [[Indiana University of Pennsylvania|Indiana State University]] Alumni Association.<ref>{{cite web |last1=McCormick |first1=Mike |title=The amazing life of Willa Beatrice Brown |url=https://www.tribstar.com/community/the-amazing-life-of-willa-beatrice-brown/article_33082107-864e-5e6c-a533-83cadb601f43.html |website=Tribune-Star |accessdate= April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n*Historical marker #238, located at the intersection of Race and Washington Streets in [[Glasgow, Kentucky]].<ref name=\"The Historical Marker Database 2016\">{{cite web | title=Willa Brown Chappell Historical Marker | website=The Historical Marker Database | date=June 16, 2016 | url=https://www.hmdb.org/m.asp?m=88118 | access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref> The marker was erected in recognition of Willa Brown Chappell, \"the first African American woman to earn a pilot's license in the United States\".<ref name=\"KY Womens History Project 2014\">{{cite web | title=Historical Markers, (page 2) | website=Kentucky Women's History Project | date=June 20, 2014 | url=http://www.kywomenshistoryproject.com/historical-markers-page-2/ | access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Riddle\">{{cite web | last=Riddle | first=Becky | title=Tour - Explore KY's New Historical Markers | website=ExploreKYHistory | url=https://explorekyhistory.ky.gov/tours/show/17 | access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist-la}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{cite web | title=The Maker of Pilots: Aviator and Civil Rights Activist Willa Beatrice Brown \u2013 Pieces of History | website=Pieces of History \u2013 A blog of the U.S. National Archives | date=2019-10-22 | url=https://prologue.blogs.archives.gov/2019/10/22/the-maker-of-pilots-aviator-and-civil-rights-activist-willa-beatrice-brown/ | access-date=2020-04-13}}\n*{{cite web\n| title = Aviation\n| last1 = Freydberg\n| first1 = Elizabeth Amelia Hadley\n| url = http://search.credoreference.com/content/entry/rcuswh/aviation/0\n| website = Credo\n| publisher = Houghton Mifflin Company\n| accessdate = 9 September 2017\n}}\n*{{cite book|title=Women aviators : 26 stories of pioneer flights, daring missions, and record-setting journeys|last1=Gibson|first1=Karen Bush|date=2013|publisher=Chicago Review Press|location=Chicago, Ill.|isbn=9781613745403|edition=1st|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/womenaviators26s0000gibs}}\n*{{cite book|title=Black women in the Armed Forces, 1942-1974 : (a pictorial history)|last1=Johnson|first1=Jesse J.|date=1974|publisher=Johnson|location=Hampton, Va.|isbn=9780915044115|edition=1st}}\n\n{{Kentucky Women Remembered|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brown, Willa}}\n[[Category:1906 births]]\n[[Category:1992 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Glasgow, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:African-American educators]]\n[[Category:20th-century American educators]]\n[[Category:African-American female military personnel]]\n[[Category:American women in World War II]]\n[[Category:Indiana State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Women in the United States Army]]\n[[Category:American female aviators]]\n[[Category:Kentucky women aviators]]\n[[Category:African-American aviators]]\n[[Category:African-American female aviators]]\n[[Category:Illinois Republicans]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{short description|American aviator, educator, activist}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name        = Willa Brown\n|image       = \"Willa Beatrice Brown, a 31-year-old Negro American, serves her country by training pilots for the U.S. Army Air Forces. - NARA - 535717.jpg\n|alt         =\n|caption     = Brown as a lieutenant in the [[United States Civil Air Patrol]]\n|birth_date  = {{birth date|mf=yes|1906|01|22}}\n|birth_place = [[Glasgow, Kentucky]], US\n|death_date  = {{death date and age|mf=yes|1992|07|18|1906|01|22}}\n|death_place = [[Chicago, Illinois]], US\n|other_names = Willa Brown Chappell\n|known_for   = [[Civil rights]] leader<br/>First female African American pilot licensed in the United States<br/>First African American officer in the United States Civil Air Patrol<br/>First African American woman to run for [[United States Congress]]\n|occupation  = [[Pilot (aeronautics)|Pilot]], [[lobbyist]], [[activist]], [[teacher]]\n|spouse   = {{Marriage|Wilbur Hardaway|November 24, 1929|1931|div}}<br>{{Marriage|[[Cornelius Coffey]]|7 February 1947|end=div}}<br>{{Marriage|Rev. J. H. Chappell|1955|end=death}}\n}}\n'''Willa Beatrice Brown''' (January 22, 1906 \u2013 July 18, 1992) was an American [[Pilot (aeronautics)|aviator]], [[lobbyist]], [[teacher]], and [[Civil Rights Movement|civil rights]] activist.<ref name=\"anb\">{{cite web |last1=Gubert |first1=Betty Kaplan |title=Brown, Willa (1906-1992), pilot and aviation educator |url=http://www.anb.org/articles/20/20-01864.html |website=American National Biography |publisher=Oxford University Press |accessdate=31 March 2020 |language=en| url-access=subscription}}</ref> She was the first [[African American]] woman to earn a pilot's license in the United States,<ref name=\"blackpast\">{{Cite web|title = Brown, Willa B. (1906\u20131992) |url = http://www.blackpast.org/aah/brown-willa-b-1906-1992|website = The Black Past|author=Davis, Edmond|access-date = 2016-02-09}}</ref> the first African American woman to run for the [[United States Congress]], first African American officer in the [[Civil Air Patrol]], and first woman in the U.S. to have both a pilot's license and an aircraft mechanic's license.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\"DOM\"/> \n\nShe was a lifelong advocate for gender and racial equality in the field of aviation as well as in the military. She not only lobbied the U.S. government to integrate the [[United States Army Air Corps]] and include African Americans in the Civilian Pilot Training Program (CPTP), she and [[Cornelius Coffey]] co-founded the [[Coffey School of Aeronautics]], distinguishing it as the first private flight training academy owned and operated by African Americans in the United States. She trained hundreds of pilots, several of whom went on to become [[Tuskegee Airmen]]; the creation of the Tuskegee Airmen has been credited to Brown's training efforts.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Our History {{!}} 99s in Aviation History {{!}} Women in Aviation |first=Kelli|last=Grant|url = http://www.ninety-nines.org/women-in-aviation-article.htm|website = The Ninety-Nines, Inc.|access-date =February 9, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"kchr.ky.gov 2020\">{{cite web | title=Willa Brown Chappell | website=kchr.ky.gov | date=2020-03-31 | url=https://kchr.ky.gov/ggbk/Pages/gbk33.aspx | access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nBrown remained politically and socially active in [[Chicago]] long after the Coffey School closed in 1945. She ran in Congressional primary elections in 1946 and 1950 and taught in the Chicago Public School System until 1971, when she retired at age 65. Following her retirement, she served on the Federal Aviation Administration's Women's Advisory Committee until 1974.\n\n== Early life ==\nWilla Beatrice Brown was born to Reverend and Mrs. Erice B. Brown on January 22, 1906, in [[Glasgow, Kentucky]].<ref name=\"blackpast\"/> She graduated from Wiley High School in [[Terre Haute, Indiana]], and attended [[Indiana State University|Indiana State Teachers College]] where she graduated in 1927 with a bachelor's degree. Ten years later she earned an [[M.B.A.]] from [[Northwestern University]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|title=Black Women in America: An Historical Encyclopedia|year=1994|publisher=Indiana University Press | location= Bloomington |isbn=0-253-32774-1 | pages=184\u2013185 | chapter=Brown, Willa Beatrice (1906\u20131992)|first=Elizabeth Hadley|last=Freydberg}}</ref><ref name=\"Davis 2012\">{{cite web | last=Davis | first=Edmond | title=Willa B. Brown (1906-1992) | website=BlackPast | date=2012-07-25 | url=https://www.blackpast.org/african-american-history/brown-willa-b-1906-1992/ | access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nBrown taught in [[Gary, Indiana]] at [[Emerson High School (Indiana)|Emerson High School]]'s [[Theodore Roosevelt College and Career Academy#History|Roosevelt Annex]] from 1927 to 1932.<ref name=\"Davis 2012\"/><ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\"/> She then moved to Chicago, where she worked in a variety of jobs, including secretarial work, social work, and teaching.<ref name=\"notable-black-american-women\">{{cite book |last1=Smith |first1=Jessie Carney |title=Notable Black American women |publisher=Gale Research |isbn=978-0810391772 |pages=69\u201371}}</ref> In 1934, she met [[John Robinson (aviator)|John C. Robinson]], who introduced her to the Challenger Air Pilots Association, a group of African American pilots.<ref name=\"anb\"/>\n\n== Aviation career ==\n[[File:Young Willa Brown.jpg|thumb|A young Willa Brown on an airfield]]\n[[File:Lola Albright and Willa Brown.jpg|thumb|Lola Albright (left) and Willa Brown (right) at Harlem Airport, Chicago Illinois, USA]]\nIn 1934, Brown began studying at Chicago's racially segregated Harlem Field with certified flight instructor [[Cornelius Coffey]], an expert in the field of aviation mechanics. She was one of few women who attended [[Curtiss\u2013Wright Aeronautical University]] where she studied aircraft maintenance and earned an aircraft mechanic's license in 1935.<ref name=\"DOM\">{{cite web | title=Masterful Willa Brown (1906-1992) | website=DOM Magazine | date=2010-01-01 | url=https://dommagazine.com/article/masterful-willa-brown-1906-1992 | access-date=2020-04-05}}</ref><ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\">{{cite book |last1=Gubert |first1=Betty Kaplan |last2=Sawyer |first2=Miriam |last3=Fannin |first3=Caroline |title=Distinguished African Americans in aviation and space science |publisher=Oryx Press |isbn=978-1573562461 |pages=49\u201352|location=Westport, Conn.|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/distinguishedafr00gube}}</ref> She earned a private pilot's license in 1938<ref>{{cite news |title=Young Woman Flyer Gets Pilot License: Willa Brown, Chicago Aviatrix, Can Carry Passengers, Give Instructions or Make Cross-Country Flights |work=The Pittsburgh Courier |date=2 July 1938 |page=11}}</ref> and a commercial pilot's license in 1939, becoming the first African American woman to earn either type of license in the United States.<ref name=\"anb\" /><ref name=\"chicago-tribune\">{{cite news |title=Chicago and the Tuskegee Airmen |work=Chicago Tribune |date=January 19, 2015  |page=Sec. 1 - 14 |url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/opinion/editorials/ct-tuskegee-airmen-chicago-world-war-ii-willa-brown-edit-0119-jm-20150119-story.html}}</ref>{{efn|[[Bessie Coleman]] was the first black American, male or female, to earn an international pilot's license which she obtained in France in the 1920s, whereas Brown was the first black American woman to earn a pilot's license in the U.S.<ref name=DOM/><ref name=\"kchr.ky.gov 2020\" /><ref name=\"chicago-tribune\" /><ref name=\"Dawson Bowles 2005 p. 5\">{{cite book | last=Dawson | first=V.P. | last2=Bowles | first2=M.D. | title=Realizing the Dream of Flight: Biographical Essays in Honor of the Centennial of Flight, 1903-2003 | publisher=National Aeronautics and Space Administration, NASA History Division, Office of External Relations | series=NASA SP | year=2005 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NpIpJI7nYV4C&pg=PA5 | access-date=2020-04-05 | page=5}}</ref>}}\n\nWilla Brown, Cornelius Coffey and Enoch P. Waters worked together to form the National Negro Airmen Association of America, later renamed to National Airmen's Association of America which was incorporated in 1939. Their primary mission was to attract more interest in aviation, help develop a better understanding in the field of aeronautics, and increase African American participation in both fields.<ref name=\"Lest We Forget 1939\">{{cite web | title=National Airmen Association of America: Tuskegee Airmen | website=Lest We Forget | date=1939-08-16 | url=http://lestweforget.hamptonu.edu/page.cfm?uuid=9FEC42B7-EB34-45CE-CC673CA72120E420 | access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> Brown was the national secretary and president of the organization's Chicago branch, and an activist for racial equality. She also took on public relations duties for the organization, and flew to colleges and spoke on the radio to get African Americans interested in flying.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\"/> She and Coffey started the Coffey School of Aeronautics in Chicago, located at Harlem Airport. They established the school for the purpose of training black pilots and teaching aviation mechanics.<ref name=\"cap-bio\">{{cite web |last1=Montague |first1=Carlos |title=Willa Brown: Pioneer for Female & African American Aviation |url=https://www.cap.news/willa-brown-pioneer-for-female--african-american-aviation/ |website=Willa Brown: Pioneer for Female & African American Aviation |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=en-us}}</ref> \n\n[[File:LIEUT. WILLA BROWN - AVIATRIX-MAKER OF PILOTS - NARA - 535627.tif|thumb|Office for Emergency Management publication featuring Brown]]\nShe lobbied the government as an advocate for the integration of black pilots into a then-segregated [[United States Army Air Corps|Army Air Corps]] and federal [[Civilian Pilot Training Program]] (CPTP).  She also worked to disprove a 1925 [[United States Army War College|Army War College]] study which had deemed African Americans unfit to fly.<ref name=\"chicago-tribune\" /> She lobbied the federal government to award CPTP contracts to train African American pilots. In 1940, she was appointed coordinator of the Chicago units of the CPTP, and the Coffey School was selected by the U.S. Army Air Corps as a feeder school to provide black students to its pilot training program.<ref name=\"notable-black-american-women\" /> Nearly 200 students from the school went on to join the [[Tuskeegee Airmen]].<ref name=\"tuskegee-airmen\">{{cite web |title=Willa Beatrice Brown |url=http://tuskegeeairmen.org/wp-content/uploads/Willa-Brown-Bio.pdf |website=Tuskegee Airmen Inc. |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> In 1942, she attained the rank of Lieutenant in Civil Air Patrol Squadron 613-6, becoming the first African American officer in the Civil Air Patrol.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\"/> She was later appointed war-training service coordinator for the [[Civil Aeronautics Authority]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Willa Brown |url=http://www.hill.af.mil/library/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=5858 |website=Hill Air Force Base |accessdate=30 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160328143509/http://www.hill.af.mil/library/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=5858 |archivedate=28 Mar 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== Postwar career ==\nIn 1946, Brown ran in the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] primary elections for [[Illinois's 1st congressional district]], becoming the first African American woman to run in a congressional primary election. Her campaign focused on improving the opportunities for African Americans, including creating an airport owned and used by African Americans.<ref>{{cite news |title=Willa B. Brown Views Politics as New Crusade |work=Chicago Daily Tribune |date=31 Mar 1946 |page=S4}}</ref> She was defeated by William E. King.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wilson |first1=Edward |title=Busbey Victory Outstanding in Congress Races  |work=Chicago Daily Tribune |date=11 Apr 1946 |page=2}}</ref> She ran for the same Congressional seat in the 1950 Republican primary election, and was defeated by [[Archibald Carey Jr.]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Harold |title=G. O. P. Starts Work to Regain Congress Posts: Leaders Hail Primary Spats as Robustness |work=Chicago Daily Tribune |date=13 Apr 1950 |page=19}}</ref>\n\nBrown returned to teaching in high schools from 1962 until her retirement in 1971. She taught business and aeronautics.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\" /> She served on the Women's Advisory Committee of the [[Federal Aviation Administration]] from 1972 to 1975. She was the first black woman to serve on that committee.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\"/>\n\n== Personal life ==\nBrown was married three times. Her first marriage was to Wilbur J. Hardaway, an African American firefighter. They met while Brown was teaching in Gary, Indiana, married in 1929, and divorced in 1931.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\"/>\n\nBrown was described as follows:\n{{quote|text=When Willa Brown, a shapely young brownskin woman, wearing white johdpurs, a form fitting white jacket and white boots, strode into our newsroom, in 1936, she made such a stunning appearance that all the typewriters suddenly went silent...Unlike most visitors, [she] wasn't at all bewildered. She had a confident bearing and there was an undercurrent of determination in her husky voice as she announced, not asked, that she wanted to see me.|author=Enoch P. Waters<ref>{{Cite news |last=Bolden |first=Tonya |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8j6pDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT54&lpg=PT54 |title=Changing the Equation: 50+ US Black Women in STEM |date=March 3, 2020 |access-date=April 14, 2020 |publisher=Abrams |language=en |isbn=978-1-68335-629-5}}</ref>}}\n\nIn 1947, she and Cornelius Coffey married, but the marriage did not last long. Her final marriage was to Reverend J. H. Chappell, pastor of the Chicago West Side Community Church, in 1955.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\"/> She was a widow by 1991.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/26618726/black-female-flyer-gave-life-to-aviation/ |title=Black female flyer gave life to aviation |date=March 23, 1991 |work=The Dispatch |access-date=April 13, 2020 |pages=4}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and recognition ==\n*In 1939, Brown was cited in the 76th [[Congressional Record]] for achievements in aviation.<ref name=\"distinguished-african-americans\" />\n*''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine profiled Brown in its September 25, 1939 issue.<ref>{{Cite magazine|date=September 25, 1939|volume=34|issue=13|page=20|periodical=[[TIME Magazine]]|title=School for Willa}}</ref>\n*In 2002, [[Women in Aviation International]] named Brown one of the 100 most influential women in aviation and space.<ref>{{cite web |title=100 Most Influential Women in the Aviation and Aerospace Industry {{!}} Women in Aviation International |url=https://www.wai.org/pioneers/100womenscript |website=www.wai.org |accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n*In 2003, a decade after her death, Willa Beatrice Brown was inducted into the [[Kentucky Aviation Hall of Fame]].<ref name=\"DOM\" /><ref name=\"Kentucky Women\">{{cite web | title=Willa Beatrice Brown | website=Kentucky Women's History Project | date=June 20, 2014| url=http://www.kywomenshistoryproject.com/willa-beatrice-brown-2/ | access-date=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n*In 2010, Brown was awarded the Distinguished Alumni Award by the [[Indiana University of Pennsylvania|Indiana State University]] Alumni Association.<ref>{{cite web |last1=McCormick |first1=Mike |title=The amazing life of Willa Beatrice Brown |url=https://www.tribstar.com/community/the-amazing-life-of-willa-beatrice-brown/article_33082107-864e-5e6c-a533-83cadb601f43.html |website=Tribune-Star |accessdate= April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n*Historical marker #238, located at the intersection of Race and Washington Streets in [[Glasgow, Kentucky]].<ref name=\"The Historical Marker Database 2016\">{{cite web | title=Willa Brown Chappell Historical Marker | website=The Historical Marker Database | date=June 16, 2016 | url=https://www.hmdb.org/m.asp?m=88118 | access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref> The marker was erected in recognition of Willa Brown Chappell, \"the first African American woman to earn a pilot's license in the United States\".<ref name=\"KY Womens History Project 2014\">{{cite web | title=Historical Markers, (page 2) | website=Kentucky Women's History Project | date=June 20, 2014 | url=http://www.kywomenshistoryproject.com/historical-markers-page-2/ | access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Riddle\">{{cite web | last=Riddle | first=Becky | title=Tour - Explore KY's New Historical Markers | website=ExploreKYHistory | url=https://explorekyhistory.ky.gov/tours/show/17 | access-date=April 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist-la}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*{{cite web | title=The Maker of Pilots: Aviator and Civil Rights Activist Willa Beatrice Brown \u2013 Pieces of History | website=Pieces of History \u2013 A blog of the U.S. National Archives | date=2019-10-22 | url=https://prologue.blogs.archives.gov/2019/10/22/the-maker-of-pilots-aviator-and-civil-rights-activist-willa-beatrice-brown/ | access-date=2020-04-13}}\n*{{cite web\n| title = Aviation\n| last1 = Freydberg\n| first1 = Elizabeth Amelia Hadley\n| url = http://search.credoreference.com/content/entry/rcuswh/aviation/0\n| website = Credo\n| publisher = Houghton Mifflin Company\n| accessdate = 9 September 2017\n}}\n*{{cite book|title=Women aviators : 26 stories of pioneer flights, daring missions, and record-setting journeys|last1=Gibson|first1=Karen Bush|date=2013|publisher=Chicago Review Press|location=Chicago, Ill.|isbn=9781613745403|edition=1st|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/womenaviators26s0000gibs}}\n*{{cite book|title=Black women in the Armed Forces, 1942-1974 : (a pictorial history)|last1=Johnson|first1=Jesse J.|date=1974|publisher=Johnson|location=Hampton, Va.|isbn=9780915044115|edition=1st}}\n\n\n{{Kentucky Women Remembered|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brown, Willa}}\n[[Category:1906 births]]\n[[Category:1992 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Glasgow, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:African-American educators]]\n[[Category:20th-century American educators]]\n[[Category:African-American female military personnel]]\n[[Category:American women in World War II]]\n[[Category:Indiana State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Women in the United States Army]]\n[[Category:American female aviators]]\n[[Category:Kentucky women aviators]]\n[[Category:African-American aviators]]\n[[Category:African-American female aviators]]